  <discussion>Deinandra mohavensis is known from the Peninsular Ranges (San Jacinto Mountains, Palomar Mountains, Anza Bench) and southernmost Sierra Nevada (Short Canyon, Jawbone Canyon region), and San Bernardino Mountains (where possibly extirpated). As noted by A. C. Sanders et al. (1997), D. mohavensis occurs in unusually mesic habitats for Deinandra (somewhat similar to situations where D. arida and D. floribunda occur) and has a highly disjunct distribution. It is in the Center for Plant Conservation’s National Collection of Endangered Plants.</discussion>
